'''Fljótsdæla saga''' ({{Audio|Is-Fljótsdæla saga.oga|listen}}) is one of the [[Icelandic sagas]]. It is probably the last one written, perhaps from about 1500, probably by an author in the East Fjords, and is a sequel to [[Hrafnkels saga]].

The story revolves around the lives and times of the residents of the [[Fljótsdalur]] region in [[Iceland]], including Helgi Ásbjarnarson and Helgi and Grímr, sons of Droplaug, a pair of brothers who have their own saga, [[Droplaugarsona saga]].

==Translations==
The saga was translated into English by John Porter in 1997:

''The Saga of the People of Fljotsdal''. Translated by John Porter. In: Viðar Hreinsson (General Editor): ''The complete sagas of Icelanders'' including 49 tales. Reykjavík: Leifur Eiríksson Publishing, 1997. Vol. IV. pp.&nbsp;379–433. {{ISBN|9979-9293-4-0}}.

