'''Lesser Caucasus''', also called '''Caucasus Minor''' is second of the two main [[mountain range]]s of [[Caucasus mountains]], of length about {{convert|600|km|mi|abbr=on}}. The western portion of the Lesser Caucasus overlaps and converges with the high [[plateau]] of [[Eastern Anatolia]], in the far northeast of [[Turkey]].

It runs parallel to the [[Greater Caucasus]], at a distance averaging about {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} south from [[Likhi Range]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) and limits the [[Armenian Highland]] from the North and North-East.

It is connected to the Greater Caucasus by the Likhi Range (Georgia) and separated from it by the [[Kolkhida Lowland]] (Georgia) in the West and [[Kura-Aras Lowland]] (Azerbaijan) (by [[Kura (Caspian Sea)|Kura River]]) in the East.

The highest peak is [[Aragats]], {{convert|4090|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica" />

The borders between [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Turkey]], [[Armenia]], and [[Azerbaijan]] run through the range, although its crest does not usually define the border.

== Component ranges ==
{{Unreferenced section|date=October 2018}}
The Lesser Caucasus mountain system does not have a single continuous mountain range.  It consists of four main parts:

# Aran-kuh (mountains of [[Talysh Mountains|Talysh]] and [[Arasbaran|Karadag]]) which runs from [[Caspian sea]] to the [[Araxes river]] in [[Iran]] and [[Azerbaijan]].
# Caucasus Minor, mountains located from [[Meghri]] (the border of [[Armenia]] with [[Iran]]) to the plateau of Ashotsk,[[Javakheti|Javakhetia]] and [[:es:Príncipes de Lori-Somkhetia|Somkhetia]] (the border of [[Armenia]] with [[Georgia (country)|Georgia)]]<nowiki/>most of which in Antiquity and Medieval was called ''[[Syunik (historic province)|Siunia Caucasiana (]]Geography of [[Ravenna]]'', V-th century, [[Western Roman empire]]).
# [[Adjara]]-[[Trialeti]] basin ranges, (also called [[Meskheti|Moskhis]] mountains), in south-western [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], passing from [[Javakheti|Javahetia]] to the border of [[Adjara|Adjaria]] with [[Turkey]]
# The mountains of [[Lazistan]] and [[Pontica]] in [[Turkey]], also called the [[Çoruh River|Tchorokh]] mountains.

== Naming controversy ==        

The range was historically called [[Anticaucasus]] or Anti-Caucasus [[Greek language|(Greek]]: Αντι-Καύκασος, [[Russian language|Russian]]: Антикавка́з, Анти-Кавка́з).  This usage is commonly found in older sources.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fAuWI72wR-UC&pg=PA547&lpg=PA547&dq=lesser+caucasus+historical+name+anticaucasus&source=bl&ots=EB_W28l2rk&sig=IheVpdBmFv878aeY07bv41LriGg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiQjfnG1_ndAhUmrlkKHcQ1AyY4ChDoATADegQIBhAB#v=onepage&q=lesser%20caucasus%20historical%20name%20anticaucasus&f=false|title=The Encyclopædia Britannica: A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, Literature and General Information|date=1911|publisher=[Cambridge] University Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Es0LAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA264&dq=anti+caucasus&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiy2Lan1fndAhXMx1kKHbY7CsMQ6AEIXjAJ#v=onepage&q=anti%20caucasus&f=false|title=A Bird's-eye View of the World|last=Reclus|first=Onésime|date=1892|publisher=Ticknor|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=td9EAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA78&lpg=PA78&dq=%22This+line+passed+along+the+south+coast+of+the+Black+Sea+through+Asia+Minor,+the+AntiCaucasus,+and+the+Kopet-dagh,+which+were+connected+farther+east,+by+hypothetical+ranges+traced+across+Afghanistan+and+the+Pamirs%22&source=bl&ots=BZHw6v1P9r&sig=InJNZk68pT2Ac9BvAcP057flhn4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjel5Sky_ndAhXBjVkKHWzQDjQQ6AEwAHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22This%20line%20passed%20along%20the%20south%20coast%20of%20the%20Black%20Sea%20through%20Asia%20Minor,%20the%20AntiCaucasus,%20and%20the%20Kopet-dagh,%20which%20were%20connected%20farther%20east,%20by%20hypothetical%20ranges%20traced%20across%20Afghanistan%20and%20the%20Pamirs%22&f=false|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica ...: A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences and General Literature ... in Thirty Volumes with New American Supplement|date=1902|publisher=Werner Company|language=en}}</ref>  Current usage tends towards using the name Lesser Caucasus, but Anticaucasus can still be found in modern texts.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.119845|title=Perspective In Geomorphology Volume I|last=Sharma|first=h s|date=1981}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maisuradze|first=G.M.|date=1989-08-15|title=Anthropogene of the anticaucasus|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248289074_Anthropogene_of_the_anticaucasus|journal=Palaeogeography Palaeoclimatology Palaeoecology - PALAEOGEOGR PALAEOCLIMATOL|volume=72|pages=53–62|doi=10.1016/0031-0182(89)90131-4}}</ref>

